To compile GEANT code, all the .cc and .hh files:
`cd build`
`cmake ..`
`make -j`
`./ecalSim`
----------------------------------------------
Within the GEANT UI:
`/run/beamOn 5` // Simulate 5 particles entering the EMCal
----------------------------------------------
There are two cases of interest: 1) I want the GUI to see the particle shower and get pretty photos.  2) I need to turn the GUI off so that I can get data of 10,000 collisions or something large.  Here is how to trigger between these two cases:
1) In the init_vis.mac macro, `/vis/scene/endOfEventAction accumulate 10`
   In the vis.mac macro, `/tracking/storeTrajectory 1`
2) In the init_vis.mac macro, `/vis/scene/endOfEventAction refresh`
   In the vis.mac macro, `/tracking/storeTrajectory 0`
----------------------------------------------
To run a macro that automates bash commands or GUI commands:
`./ecalSim ../macros/run_job.mac`
This will execute the commands of that macro!  So, currently, I have that macro disabling drawing and GUI usage and running over 10000 events.  Convenient way of handling things.
----------------------------------------------
To plot the results in Python, I have created a directory called `.plotstuff`
Go there and activate the venv with `source /bin/activate`
Then, `python3 plot.py`
This runs the `plot.py` python script and outputs a pretty histogram.  Can use this for pretty plotting for now.  Should figure out VS Code instead though.
----------------------------------------------
To run the bash script that will automate running over various energies: `bash autoLoop.sh`
----------------------------------------------
Running a Job: If I want to run over 100,000 events in batch mode,
- Go to computer settings and turn off sleep/power-down timers
- `nohup ./executable_script.sh > name_of_log_file.log 2>&1 &`
- To check on status and get job ID number: `ps -ef | grep executable_script.sh`
- To see most recent activity in the job: `tail -f name_of_log_file.log`

----------------------------------------------
The ecalSim.cc file is the workhorse of the operation.  It initializes each GEANT simulated event, controls the interactive GUI and is called whenever one wishes to simulate N events.
